Toronto Blue Jays played against the Minnesota Twins in the American League Wildcard Series. The first game of the series was played on October 3rd when the Twins beat the Blue Jays by a score of 3-1. As a baseball fan, I wanted to statistically analyze and visualize certain aspects of this game. Rather than predictive modelling, this project simply focuses on the postgame analysis of the first game of the American League Wildcard Series.

Plate Discipline¶

One thing that really impressed me during the game was the plate discipline shown by the Minnesota Twins hitters (and rookies). Blue Jays pitcher Kevin Gausman gave away 3 walks during the game. While this on its own might not seem high, it is interesting when you realise that he gave away 3 walks in 4 innings in this game (0.75 walks/innings pitched), whereas during the regular season, he had given just 55 walks in 185 innings pitched (0.3 walks/innings pitched).

The first part of this analysis thus focuses on the plate discipline of the 2 teams. To see this, I have analyzed whether the hitters swung at a given pitch, given its horizontal and vertical position when it crossed home plate.

jays['swing'] = np.where(jays.description.isin(['ball','blocked_ball','hit_by_pitch','called_strike']), 0, 1)

fastball = ['FF','SI']
breaking = ['CU','ST']
offspeed = ['CH']

jays['pitch_type_cat'] = ""

jays['pitch_type_cat'] = np.where(jays['pitch_type'].isin(fastball), 'fastball', jays['pitch_type_cat'])
jays['pitch_type_cat'] = np.where(jays['pitch_type'].isin(breaking), 'breaking', jays['pitch_type_cat'])
jays['pitch_type_cat'] = np.where(jays['pitch_type'].isin(offspeed), 'offspeed', jays['pitch_type_cat'])

The first visualization simply focuses on whether the hitter swung at a pitch, given its horizontal and vertical position when it crossed the plate. As expected, most of the pitches outside the red box (strike zone) are blue, showing that the Blue Jays hitters did not swing at it. However, we do notice 2 regions (bottom right of the plate and near the top left) where Blue Jays hitters swung at pitches outside the strike zone.

The next visualization breaks down the previous analysis by hitter. Each color in the chart above represents a different Blue Jays hitter, along with whether they swung at a particular pitch. There are some interesting patterns / strategies that we can observe in the visualization above:

  1. All the pitches that were slightly outside the top left side of the strike and had a swing, were pitched to batter 672386 (Alejandro Kirk). In fact, we can see that most of the pitches to Kirk were thrown outside the strike zone. The Twins had identified Kirk as a player who is likely to swing at a pitch even if it is outside the strike zone, and this is a strategy that seems to have worked.
  2. Similarly, player 666182 (Bo Bichette) also seems to have swung at pitches outside the strike zone on the lower right corner.
  3. Players 593160 (Whit Merrifield) and 624415 (Cavin Biggio) show very good plate discipline and have not swung at pitches outside the strike zone.
  • light blue always pitched outside
  • brownish yellow also pitched outside
  • dark blue and dark green have very good plate discipline

The final swing analysis tries to break down the analysis by the pitcher and pitch type. It must be noted that the starting pitcher is more likely to have more data points than the other pitchers in the bullpen. From this visualization, we see that Pablo Lopez was successful in getting the Blue Jays hitters to swing at outside strike zone pitches with his breaking pitch at the bottom right side, and fastballs to the top left.

Statistical Analysis¶

The next part of the analysis focuses on the Blue Jays hitters. We try to analyze how the hitters fared against different pitch types and pitch characteristics throughout the game.

First, we look at:

  1. Total count of each pitch type faced by the Blue Jays hitters
  2. Total strikes per pitch type
  3. Average strikes per pitch type

From the results, we see that the Twins pitchers threw a lot of Fastballs and Sweepers to the Blue Jays hitters. Unsurprisingly, these pitches also resulted in the most strikes with 28.6% of the strikes coming from Fastballs and 37.1% coming from Sweepers. However, it is also interesting to note that the Twins pitchers used their variations really well because even though the number of curveballs thrown was the lowest, it had the highest efficiency in getting strikes (more than 50%).

Next, we look at the pitches breakdown for each individual batter. The chart above was created with Tableau, and we can see that the Twins had a different strategy for different Blue Jays hitters. For players 543807 (George Springer) and 595281 (Kevin Kiermaier), a large proportion of the pitches were 4-seam fastballs. As opposed to this, most of the pitches thrown to player 624415 (Cavin Biggio) were Changeup or Sweeper while the majority of pitches to player 666182 (Bo Bichette) were Sweeper.

We can also see that these strategies and variations have worked really well for the Twins, as they got 4 strikes from Sweeper pitches on both Biggio and Bichette. Player 672386 (Kirk) on the other hand seems to have at least dealt with the variation well in terms of strikes. Despite being targeted by a lot of Sinkers, he did not give away a single strike on this kind of pitch.

For the final analysis, we try to analyze whether the characteristics of the particular pitch had an impact on deciding whether it resulted in a strike. For this, we look at data such as:

  1. release_speed: out of hand pitch velocity
  2. pfx_x, pfx_z: horizontal and vertical movement of the pitch
  3. vx0, vy0, vz0: the velocity of the pitch in x,y and z dimension at y = 50 feet
  4. release_spin_rate: spin rate of the pitch

While for most of the characteristics, we do not see a major difference between pitches that resulted in a strike and those that did not, we do notice that the release spin rate of the 4-Seam Fastball and Changeup is lower on average for pitches that resulted in strikes. Similarly, the Blue Jays seem to have higher average strikes on Curveballs that have a lower velocity in the z-dimension or Sweeper that have a lower velocity in the x-dimension.

This analysis can be extended to individual players over the entire season, to further understand the characteristics of the pitches that lead to higher average strikeouts for the batter.

The goal of this study was to statistically analyze and visualize the match between Toronto Blue Jays and Minnesota Twins. From our analysis, we were able to identify certain important takeaways from the game, including the pitch discipline shown by the Minnesota Twins hitters and the pitch type and characteristics of pitches that the Blue Jays hitters struggled with.
